      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Many legal scholars argue that existing antitrust frameworks are fundamentally outdated because they were designed for a pre-digital economy. Current laws struggle to address the network effects and data advantages that define modern platform dominance. Regulators are increasingly finding that traditional measures of market share don't capture the true harm caused by algorithmic gatekeeping and self-preferencing. Therefore, there is a growing push for new, more adaptive regulations tailored to digital markets.",
      "source": "target",
